# Neutral source and version-control copy

Keep the repository and history free of references to assisted-editing products, chat models, or similar tooling.

## Do not include in code

Avoid in comments, docstrings, README/user docs, log messages, error strings, test names, and any committed text:

- The product name of this editor or similar IDEs marketed as AI-assisted
- Names of chat models, assistants, or vendors (e.g. generic “LLM”, “AI agent”, “GPT”, “Copilot”, “Claude”, “Gemini”, and comparable branded terms)
- Phrases like “generated by …”, “written with …”, or “this was produced by …” when they identify such tooling

Write as if the project is authored by the team: explain *what* and *why* in domain terms only.

## Do not include in git commits

Commit subjects and bodies must not mention those tools or models. Use conventional, human team voice: scope, intent, and behavior change only.

## Editor settings (so commits stay neutral)

Neutrality is not enough if the editor appends attribution trailers (e.g. product footers on every commit). In **Settings → Agents → Attribution**, disable **commit attribution** and **PR attribution** so nothing is injected into messages or pull requests. Restart the editor if a change does not take effect immediately.

## Examples

```text
❌ BAD commit: "Fix login; suggested by ChatGPT"
✅ GOOD commit: "fix(auth): reject expired OTP after max attempts"

❌ BAD comment: // TODO: ask the AI to refactor this
✅ GOOD comment: // TODO: extract shared validation for registration and resend flows
```

When unsure, describe the change in product/engineering language and omit any attribution to external assistants.
